[5] Cholera - India
Date: Thu 10 May 2007
Source: Sahara Samay [edited]
<http://www.saharasamay.com/samayhtml/articles.aspx?newsid=75022>

Waterborne diseases have begun spreading their tentacles in the national
capital [Delhi] as summer season reaches its peak. According to Sahara
Samay sources, diseases such as jaundice, cholera, and typhoid have
engulfed many areas in the capital. Water crisis forces most of the
Delhiites to drink impure water that leads to the breaking out of epidemics.
As many as 70 cases of cholera have been reported. Talking to [Sahara
Samay], a doctor warned the residents against using adulterated water.
People should wash their hands properly before taking food and after coming
back from the toilet, he added.
--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of India showing New Delhi, in the north, can be found at
<http://www.pnm.my/mtcp/images/maps/India-map.jpg>. - Mod.LL]
